SAFE HARBOR WATER POWER CORPORATION FERC ELECTRIC TARIFF
1. Availability. Safe Harbor Water Power Corporation (“Seller”) makes available under this Tariff the following services to customers with whom Seller contracts:
(a) electric energy and capacity for sale at wholesale; and (b) ancillary services, as described in Section 5 below.
2. Applicability. This Tariff is applicable to all wholesale power sales, including energy and capacity sales not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule of Seller, and applicable ancillary services.
3. Rates. All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
4. Other Terms and Conditions. All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
5. Ancillary Services. Seller also will make available to any purchaser with whom it has contracted, the ancillary services listed in this Paragraph 5.
(a) PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection.
(b) New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.
(c) New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.
(d) California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
(e) Third Party Ancillary Services: Seller offers Regulation and Frequency Response Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, and Operating Reserve-Supplemental. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating-Reserve Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation and Frequency Response Service and Reactive supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider’s OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
7. Communications. Except as otherwise agreed in writing by the purchaser and Seller, any notice, demand or request provided for in this Tariff shall be deemed to be properly given or made if set forth in writing and delivered or sent by first-class mail, postage prepaid, to Seller at its principal office or to any purchaser when sales are made to wholesale purchasers under this Tariff.
8. Compliance With Commission Regulations. Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller’s market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller’s market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller’s market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
9. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority. Seller has requested and been granted the following waivers of Commission regulations, pursuant to Commission order in Safe Harbor Water Power Corporation, Docket No. ER08-537-000:
(a) waiver of the filing requirements of subparts B and C of Part 35 of the Commission’s regulations, except as to Sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15, and 35.16, to the extent necessary, consistent with the Commission’s regulations;
(b) waiver of the accounting, reporting and other requirements of Parts 41 (accounts, records, and memoranda), 101 (uniform system of accounts), and 141 (statement and reports) of the Commission’s regulations, except Sections 141.14 and 141.15;
(c) blanket authorization for the issuance of securities or the assumption of liabilities pursuant to Section 204 of the FPA and Part 34 of the Commission’s regulations; and
(d) waiver of the affiliate restrictions under Section 35.39 of the Commission’s regulations.
10. Modification. Seller may unilaterally apply to the Commission or successor agency at any time for authority to change the terms or conditions of this Tariff under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act and the regulations promulgated thereunder.
11. Effective Date. This Tariff is effective July 1, 2014, or upon such date authorized by the Commission.
12. Seller Category. Seller is a Category 2 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. § 35.36(a), in the Northeast region. Seller is a Category 1 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. § 35.36(a), in all other regions of the United States.

SAFE HARBOR CONTRACT
THIS AGREEMENT, made as of the 1st day of September, 1982, between SAFE HARBOR WATER POWER CORPORATION, a Pennsylvania Corporation, hereinafter called “Safe Harbor,” BALTIMORE GAS AND ELECTRIC COMPANY, a Maryland Corporation, hereinafter called “Baltimore,” and PENNSYLVANIA POWER & LIGHT COMPANY, a Pennsylvania corporation, hereinafter called “Pennsylvania.”
WITNESSETH THAT,
WHEREAS, Safe Harbor owns and operates an existing hydroelectric development on the Susquehanna River at Safe Harbor, Pennsylvania, under a license from the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission expiring April 22, 2030, consisting of seven main and two auxiliary generators having an aggregate capacity of approximately 230,000 kW and desires to sell the entire output of such development; and
WHEREAS, Safe Harbor is expanding its generating capacity by adding five generating units having an aggregate capacity of 187,500 kW, as approved by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, and desires to sell the additional output of such additional hydroelectric development, when and if available; and
WHEREAS, Baltimore is engaged in the generation, purchase and sale of electrical power and energy in the City of Baltimore and vicinity and owns two-thirds of the stock of Safe Harbor, one-half of which is voting and the other one-half non-voting stock, and desires to continue to purchase two-thirds of the capacity and energy available from Safe Harbor’s existing plant and additional hydroelectric plant under construction; and
WHEREAS, Pennsylvania is engaged in the generation, purchase and sale of electrical power and energy in the eastern part of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania and is the owner of one-third of the stock of Safe Harbor, all of which is voting stock, and desires to purchase one-third of the capacity and energy available from Safe Harbor’s existing plant and additional hydroelectric plant under construction;
NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises and of the mutual covenants and agreements herein set forth, Safe Harbor, Baltimore and Pennsylvania do hereby agree each with the others as follows:
ARTICLE 1

Effective Date, Duration of Agreement and Cancellation of Prior contract
1.1	Subject to the approval of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, this agreement shall become effective on the first day of November, 1982, and shall remain in force until the expiration of the Safe Harbor license on midnight of April 22, 2030, and for such time thereafter as Safe Harbor is the licensee from the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission of the Safe Harbor project. This contract supersedes and replaces the Safe Harbor Contract made and effective as of June 1, 1955, between Baltimore Gas and Electric Company, Pennsylvania Power & Light Company, and Safe Harbor Water Power Corporation, as amended on July 1, 1978, and November 1, 1981, except that the letter agreements between the parties dated as of June 1, 1955, July 28, 1960, October 19, 1970, and July 7, 1975, shall remain in full force and effect. 
ARTICLE 2

Capacity and Energy Entitlements
2.1	Baltimore and Pennsylvania shall be entitled to all the capacity and energy available (other than any which way be required for the performance of any duty or obligation to serve imposed on Safe Harbor by its charter or otherwise by law) from the presently existing hydroelectric plant, consisting of seven main and two auxiliary generators having an aggregate capacity of approximately 230,000 kW, and all the capacity and energy when and if available from the additional hydroelectric plant under construction, consisting of five generators having an aggregate capacity of 187,500 kW, the total entitlement of 417,500 KW to be divided between Baltimore and Pennsylvania as follows:
The part of the total capacity and daily energy available from the existing plant and additional plant under construction, measured as of the points of delivery to the facilities of Pennsylvania as set forth in Section 5.1, to which each receiving company is entitled will be called that Company’s “contract proportion.” Baltimore’s contract proportion shall be two-thirds and Pennsylvania’s contract proportion one-third.
2.2	Subject to the provisions of Section 3.1, the respective energy entitlements of Baltimore and Pennsylvania shall be delivered in amounts as requested by each of said parties, or collectively by a representative of both duly appointed by them.
2.3	In the event of an actual or threatened power shortage in their own systems or the systems with which they are interconnected, either Baltimore or Pennsylvania is entitled to draw from the Safe Harbor reservoir its contract proportion of the then available storage. When and if either company alone, in the exercise of its rights under this section, causes a drawdown of the Safe Harbor reservoir, it shall use a portion of its normal energy entitlement to compensate the other purchasing company for its loss in energy and capacity caused by the reduction in head that results from such drawdown.
ARTICLE 3

Coordination of Safe Harbor and Holtwood Operations
3.1	Subject to the provisions of Section 2.3 with respect to situations of actual or threatened power shortage, Safe Harbor and Pennsylvania shall continue to coordinate the operations of the Safe Harbor and Holtwood hydroelectric plants for the purpose of obtaining the optimum utilization of their combined hydro resources, notwithstanding that such coordination may result at certain times in reduced economy or utilization of the separate plant of either company. The parties hereto shall exchange all available information as to river flows, expected loads and plant discharges needed for such continued cooperative use of the available river flow, hydraulic heads and pondage.
ARTICLE 4

Characteristics of Supply
4.1	Unless otherwise agreed by the parties hereto, electrical energy supplied under this agreement to (1) Baltimore shall be in the form of three-phase alternating current at a nominal frequency of 60 hertz and at approximately 220,000 volts, and in the form of single-phase alternating current at a nominal frequency of 25 hertz at approximately 13,200 volts, and (2) Pennsylvania shall be in the form of three-phase alternating current at a nominal frequency of 60 hertz at approximately 2,300, 66,000 and 220,000 volts, and in the form of single-phase alternating current at a nominal frequency of 25 hertz at approximately 13,200 volts.
4.2	Safe Harbor shall at all times keep its equipment in first-class condition in accordance with good operating practice and shall arrange whenever possible to have all maintenance work done in such manner and at such times as will result in minimum overall costs to the purchasing companies.
ARTICLE 5

Points of Delivery and Transmission
5.1	60-hertz capacity and energy contracted for hereunder shall be delivered to the facilities of Pennsylvania on the high-tension side of the 220,000 volt and 66,000 volt step-up transformers at Safe Harbor and from the 2,300 volt Safe Harbor village circuit in the Manor substation tunnel and 25-hertz capacity and energy shall be delivered to the 13,200 volt bus in Pennsylvania’s Conestoga substation and/or elsewhere as the parties hereto shall agree.
Baltimore’s entitlement shall be transmitted by Pennsylvania to Baltimore in accordance with the provisions of the transmission contract made by Safe Harbor, Baltimore and Pennsylvania as of July 20, 1960, which became effective October 1, 1960.
ARTICLE 6

Metering
6.1	Safe Harbor shall provide and maintain suitable electric meters at Safe Harbor and in Pennsylvania’s Conestoga substation for the determination of the net send out from the Safe Harbor plant. This group of meters shall herein be called billing meters.
6.2	Procedure in respect to maintenance, testing, calibration and correction, registration records and precision tolerance of metering equipment shall be in accordance with good practice as may be agreed upon by the parties hereto from time to time.
6.3	Each party hereto shall provide for the other, at such other’s expense, such suitable terminals and metering connections in its respective plants as may be reasonably requested for telemetering in connection with the performance of this contract.
ARTICLE 7

Payments for Capacity and Energy
7.1	The total combined annual payment by Baltimore and Pennsylvania to Safe Harbor for capacity and energy shall be made as nearly as possible in equal monthly installments and shall be in such amount as is required to yield to Safe Harbor a fair rate of return on its rate base as hereinafter defined, after provision for all reasonable operating expenses. The term “operating expenses”, as used in this contract, shall mean and include charges or provisions for operation expense, general expenses, current maintenance and repairs, taxes, deferred taxes, and all expenses for depreciation, depletion and amortization. These expenses shall be computed using the normalization method of accounting as prescribed in Section 168 of the Internal Revenue Code. Such annual payment shall be made on the basis of a rate of return of 15.3%, and on a rate base defined as the original cost of plant in service including completed construction not yet classified, less the accumulated reserve for depreciation, depletion and amortization, plus working capital, leas accumulated deferred income taxes, calculated as of January 1 and July 1 of each year. Working capital shall be computed as the sum of the average balance of materials and supplies on hand for the prior 12 months, plus one-eighth (1/8) of the total cash operating expenses for the prior 12 months (excluding taxes, deferred taxes, and depreciation). The above payment for energy and capacity shall be subject to increases and/or decreases from time to time by order of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
7.2	The combined annual payment computed as prescribed in Section 7.1 shall be prorated between Baltimore and Pennsylvania in the ratio of their contract proportions, i.e., each shall pay to Safe Harbor its contract proportion of the total payment specified herein.
ARTICLE 8

Terms of Payment
8.1	All bills for capacity and energy as provided in Article 7 shall be rendered by Safe Harbor to Baltimore and Pennsylvania for each calendar month not later than the 10th day of the next succeeding month and shall be paid on or before the 20th day of said month.
ARTICLE 9

Audit of Costs
9.1	For the purpose of verifying Safe Harbor’s rate base and operating expenses as defined by the provisions of Article 7, Baltimore and Pennsylvania shall each have complete access to and may audit the accounts of Safe Harbor at any time.
ARTICLE 10

Causes beyond Control
10.1	If at any time during the continuance of this agreement Safe Harbor shall be prevented from supplying and Baltimore and Pennsylvania from receiving all or any part of the power and energy herein specified, by reason of war, rebellion, civil disturbance, strikes, serious epidemics, major catastrophe, or any other cause of a like nature beyond the control of either party, the obligation of Safe Harbor to supply and the obligation of Baltimore and Pennsylvania to take power and energy herein specified shall cease until such time as the party so incapacitated shall, by the exercise of reasonable diligence, be able to resume such supply or use, and a reasonable abatement in the payments by Baltimore and Pennsylvania shall be made; provided, however, that in no event shall such abatement reduce such payments to less than the respective amounts required by Safe Harbor to pay interest on its indebtedness, and sinking fund charges, if any, over and above operating expenses as defined in Section 7.1, after crediting Safe Harbor for any revenues from the sale by it of power or energy to others.
ARTICLE 11

Waiver of Rights
11.1	The failure of any party hereto to enforce from time to time a strict performance of any of the covenants and agreements herein contained, or the waiver from time to time of default on the part of any party hereto, shall not be construed as a waiver of any continued, continuing or subsequent default, or defaults, nor impair the rights of any of the parties hereto subsequently to require the strict performance of each and every covenant, agreement and understanding herein contained.
ARTICLE 12

Assignment
12.1	No party hereto shall, without the written consent of the others, assign or otherwise transfer this agreement but this agreement shall be binding upon and shall inure to the benefit of any successor corporation or corporations with which, or into which, any of the parties hereto may hereafter become consolidated or merged, and to any successor corporation or corporations to any of the parties hereto or to any corporation or corporations with which, or into which, any of the parties hereto may have been consolidated or merged, created by, or arising out of, reorganization or receivership proceedings, or otherwise by law, and to any receiver, trustee-in-bankruptcy or other legally appointed assignee of the assets, property and business of any of the parties hereto, or of such successor corporation or corporations.
 

IN WITNESS WHEREOF, the parties hereto have caused these presents to be duly executed by their respective officers, thereunto duly authorized and the respective corporate seals to the hereunto affixed as of the day and year first written above.

UNITED STATES OF AMERICA
BEFORE THE

Safe Harbor Water Power Corporation ) Docket No. ER82-763-000
OFFER OF SETTLEMENT
ON BEHALF OF
SAFE HARBOR WATER POWER CORPORATION
This offer of settlement is made by and on behalf of Safe Harbor Water Power Corporation (“Safe Harbor”) as a result of settlement discussions held with the Commission Staff and representatives of the Maryland Public Service Commission on January 14, 1983.
This settlement offer relates to the rate changes tendered for filing by Safe Harbor on August 31, 1982. These changes included: (1) raising the rate of return component of Safe Harbor’s formula rate from 12.76% to 15.30% on rate base; and (2) modifying the formula rate to provide for normalization accounting as required by § 35.25 of the Commission’s regulations and to qualify for the income tax deductions associated with the use of ACRS.
The elements of this offer of settlement are as follows:
 
- 2 -

I.	RATE CHANGES AND EFFECTIVE DATE
1.1	The formula rate shall be changed to allow a rate of return of 13.25% on rate base. The contract page incorporating this change is attached hereto as Appendix A.
1.2	The rate changes filed with respect to normalization accounting will be allowed to become effective as filed.
1.3	Effective dates: The effective date of all changes shall be December 22, 1982 (sixty days after the completion of the original filing).
II.	CONDITIONS
2.1	It is an express condition of this offer of settlement that the Commission allow all rate changes filed by Safe Harbor as modified by this offer of settlement to become effective as of December 22, 1982. It is further a condition of this settlement agreement that, in order to effectuate the effective date proposed herein, the Commission grant rehearing of its order of December 17, 1982 in this proceeding which order did not allow for an effective date during calendar year 1982, of the rate changes filed by Safe Harbor. In approving this settlement the Commission will grant rehearing of the December 17, 1982 order and authorize all rate changes, as modified in this offer of settlement, to become effective as of December 22, 1982.
2.2	The approval of this settlement agreement by the Commission shall constitute approval of normalization accounting as the basis for Safe Harbor’s rates, thereby allowing Safe Harbor to qualify for the ACRS benefits as prescribed in the Economic Recovery Tax Act of 1981.
2.3	Except as stated in paragraph 2.2 herein, approval of this offer of settlement by the Commission shall not be deemed to foreclose any party from making any contention in any other proceeding or investigation. 
2.4	This offer of settlement is expressly conditioned upon the Commission’s acceptance of all provisions hereof without change or condition.
2.5	The discussions which have produced this offer of settlement have been conducted on the explicit understanding that all offers of settlement and discussions relating thereto are and shall be privileged, shall be without prejudice to the position of any party or participant, and are not to be used in any manner in connection with these or any other proceedings involving one or all of the parties to this proceeding or otherwise. This offer of settlement is submitted on the condition that, in the event the Commission does not by order accept it in its entirety, this settlement agreement shall be deemed withdrawn and shall not constitute any part of the record in this proceeding or be used for any other purpose. This offer of settlement is made this 14th day of February, 1983 by Safe Harbor Water Power Corporation by its attorneys who represent that they are fully authorized to do so on behalf of their principal.

The term “operating expenses,” as used in this contract, shall mean and include charges or provisions for operation expenses, general expenses, current maintenance and repairs, taxes, deferred taxes, and all expenses for depreciation, depletion and amortization. SETTLEMENT AGREEMENT

Introduction

On August 31, 1989, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“FERC” or “Commission”) issued an “Order to Show Cause” in Safe Harbor Water Power Corporation, Docket No. EL89-46-000, requiring the Safe Harbor Water Power Corporation (“Safe Harbor”) to show cause why the Commission should not set Safe Harbor’s overall return under FERC Rate Schedule No. 7 for investigation and hearing. Under that rate schedule, Safe Harbor sells the entire output of its hydroelectric plant at a formulary rate to its two owners --- Baltimore Gas and Electric Company (“BG&E”) and Pennsylvania Power & Light Company (“PP&L”).
On September 21, 1989, Safe Harbor responded to the Commission’s order, contending that its existing return was reasonable. On January 24, 1990, the Commission issued an order setting Safe Harbor’s overall return for investigation and hearing. On February 5, 1990, a prehearing conference was held before Administrative Law Judge Charles E. Bullock.
Subsequently, representatives of Safe Harbor and the Commission Staff met and agreed to the Settlement set forth herein. An Explanatory Statement concerning the terms of the Settlement Agreement is contained as Attachment A.
Article I

Rate of Return
Safe Harbor and Commission Staff agree that effective January 24, 1990, the rate of return to be used in the formula rate in the Safe Harbor contract shall be equal to 10.5 percent. Attachment B, appended hereto and incorporated by reference in its entirety, is Section 7.1 of the Safe Harbor Contract revised to reflect this agreement.
Article II

Annual Return Reopener
Safe Harbor and Commission Staff agree that the Safe Harbor Contract shall not include an “annual return reopener” which provides, upon the filing of a complaint, for an annual examination of the rate of return reflected in the formula rate.
Article III

Reservations
	1.	All parties to this Settlement Agreement will cooperate in seeking its acceptance and approval by the Commission. If this Settlement Agreement, which is made pursuant to Section 602 of the Commission’s Rules of Practice and Procedure, 18 C.F.R. § 385.602, is not accepted and approved by the Commission without modification, then: (i) it shall not be binding on any party; (ii) all parties shall be deemed to have reserved all their respective rights and remedies in these proceedings; (iii) this Settlement Agreement shall not be part of the record in this proceeding and all discussions and negotiations thereon shall be privileged; and (iv) the parties shall not be obliged to negotiate further.
	2.	This Settlement Agreement is made upon the express understanding that it constitutes a negotiated comprehensive settlement with respect to the issues raised in this proceeding. Except as specifically provided herein, nothing in this Settlement Agreement shall constitute an admission by any party of the correctness or applicability of any claim, defense, rule or interpretation of law, allegation of fact, principle or method of ratemaking or cost-of-service determination and it is also agreed that the parties shall not be considered to necessarily agree with or concede the applicability of any principle or method of ratemaking cost-of-service determination, or design of rate schedule, or terms or conditions of service, or the application of any rule or interpretation of law, that may underlie, or be thought to underlie, this settlement. It is further agreed that in any future negotiation or proceeding (other than any proceeding involving the honoring, enforcement or construction of this Settlement Agreement), the parties shall not be bound or prejudiced by this Settlement Agreement.
Article IV

Nonseverability
The various provisions of this Settlement Agreement are not severable, and, unless this Settlement Agreement becomes effective in accordance with Article III, any party shall have the right to withdraw such Settlement Agreement.
The parties have signed and executed this Settlement Agreement by their duly authorized representatives this 2nd day of May, 1990.
SAFE HARBOR WATER POWER CORPORATION


By:		
	Attorney for:
	Safe Harbor Water Power Corporation

COMMISSION TRIAL STAFF


By:		
 
Attachment A

EXPLANATORY STATEMENT

The terms of the agreed upon settlement are as follows:
1.	Safe Harbor and Commission Staff agree that effective January 24, 1990, the rate of return to be used in the formula rate in the Safe Harbor Contract shall be equal to 10.5 percent (See Article I of the Settlement Agreement).
2.	Safe Harbor and Commission Staff agree that the Safe Harbor Contract shall not include an “annual return reopener” which provides, upon filing of a complaint, for an annual examination of the rate of return reflected in the formula rate. The “annual return reopener” clause was added to the Safe Harbor Contract as part of a settlement of Safe Harbor Water Power Corp., Docket No. EL88-2-000, 42 FERC ¶ 61,219 (1988). The parties agree that it can be removed from the contract in light of the Regulatory Fairness Act, Pub.L. 100-473 (See Article II of the Settlement Agreement).
3. 	Unless the Settlement Agreement is approved without modification, the agreement shall not be binding and is otherwise privileged. Moreover, Safe Harbor and Commission Staff agree that the agreement is a negotiated settlement (See Article III of the Settlement Agreement).
4.	The provisions of the Settlement Agreement are not severable and, if it is not approved in its entirety without modification, the parties reserve the right to withdraw the Settlement Agreement (See Article IV of the Settlement Agreement).

 
Article 7
Payments for Capacity and Energy
7.1	The total combined annual payment by Baltimore and Pennsylvania to Safe Harbor for capacity and energy shall be made as nearly as possible in equal monthly installments and shall be in such amount as is required to yield to Safe Harbor a fair rate of return on its rate base as hereinafter defined, after provision for all reasonable operating expenses. The term “operating expenses,” as used in this contract, shall mean and include charges or provisions for operation expense, general expenses, current maintenance and repairs, taxes, deferred taxes, and all expenses for depreciation, depletion and amortization. These expenses shall be computed using the normalization method of accounting for accelerated tax depreciation as prescribed in Section 168 of the Internal Revenue Code, and the normalization method of accounting for other tax timing differences as prescribed in Section 35.25 of the Regulations of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. Such annual payment shall be made on the basis of a rate of return of 5.65% and on a rate base defined as the original cost of plant in service including completed construction not yet classified, less the accumulated reserve for depreciation, depletion and amortization, plus working capital, less accumulated deferred income taxes, calculated as of January 1 and July 1 of each year. Working capital shall be computed as the sum of the average balance of materials and supplies on hand for the prior 12 months, plus one-eighth (1/8) of the total cash operating expenses for the prior 12 months (excluding taxes, deferred taxes, and depreciation). The above payments for energy and capacity shall be subject to increases and/or decreases from time-to-time by order of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.

The settlement rates submitted with the settlement are accepted for filing and are designated and made effective as shown on the attached Enclosure. The Commission’s approval of this settlement does not constitute approval of, or precedent regarding, any principle or issue in this proceeding.

	Within thirty (30) days from the date of this letter, any amounts collected in excess of the modified settlement rate levels shall be refunded together with interest computed under Section 35.19a of the Commission’s Regulations. Within fifteen (15) days after making such refunds, the Company shall file with this Commission a compliance report showing monthly billing determinants, revenue receipt dates, and revenues under the prior and settlement rates, the monthly revenue refund, and the monthly interest computed, together with a summary of such information for the total refund period. The Company shall furnish copies of such report to the affected wholesale customers and to each state commission within whose jurisdiction the wholesale customers distribute and sell electric energy at retail.

ASSIGNMENT AND ASSUMPTION AGREEMENT

	THIS ASSIGNMENT AND ASSUMPTION AGREEMENT, dated as of July 1, 2000 (“Assignment and Assumption Agreement”), is made and entered into by and between Baltimore Gas and Electric Company, a Maryland corporation (“Baltimore”), and Constellation Power Source Generation, Inc., a Maryland corporation and an affiliate of Baltimore (“Constellation”). Baltimore and Constellation may be referred to individually as a “Party,” and collectively as the “Parties.”

	WHEREAS, Baltimore, PPL Electric Utilities Corporation (“PPL Utilities”) and Safe Harbor Water Power Corporation (“Safe Harbor”) are parties to the “Safe Harbor Contract”, effective as of November 1, 1982, which provides, among other things, for the purchase by Baltimore and PPL Utilities of electric capacity and energy from Safe Harbor; and

	WHEREAS, Baltimore is engaged in an internal corporate realignment process which includes, among other things, the transfer of Baltimore’s stock interest in Safe Harbor to Constellation; and

	WHEREAS, as part of its corporate realignment processes, Baltimore desires to assign its interest in the Safe Harbor Contract to Constellation.

	NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the mutual agreements, covenants and conditions herein contained, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, and intending to be legally bound, Baltimore and Constellation hereby agree as follows:

	1.	Assignment. Baltimore hereby transfers and assigns to Constellation all of Baltimore’s rights in and obligations under the Safe Harbor Contract, together with all books and records associated with such Contract.

	2.	Assumption. Constellation hereby agrees to accept said assignment and agrees to assume and perform fully all of the obligations of Baltimore in accordance with the terms of the Safe Harbor Contract.

	3.	Effective Date. Such assignment and assumption shall be effective when the following have occurred: (1) this Assignment and Assumption Agreement has been duly executed and delivered by the Parties; (2) Baltimore’s transfer of its non-nuclear assets has closed; and (3) Baltimore has obtained the required consent of the other parties to the Safe Harbor Contract.

 

	IN WITNESS WHEREOF, this Assignment and Assumption Agreement has been duly executed and delivered by the Parties as of the date first above written.

Baltimore Gas and Electric Company		Constellation Power Source Generation, Inc.

SAFE HARBOR WATER POWER CORPORATION
Reactive Power and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service
Safe Harbor Water Power Corporation ("Safe Harbor") provides Reactive Supply and Voltage Control from Generation Sources Service ("Reactive Service") from its hydroelectric generating facility located in Safe Harbor, Pennsylvania ("Facility") in the control area administered by the PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") in order to assist in maintaining transmission voltage within acceptable limits on the PJM transmission system. This Reactive Service Tariff sets forth Safe Harbor's revenue requirement for the provision of Reactive Service from the facility pursuant to Schedule 2 of the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff, which provides for PJM to pay generation owners their monthly revenue requirements for Reactive Service.
Total charges for any 12-month period will not be less than the sum of the annual charges specified below. This Reactive Service Tariff shall be effective upon the date authorized by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
REACTIVE SERVICE REVENUE REQUIREMENT:
The total annual revenue requirement is $3,637,224.96.
The total monthly revenue requirement is $3,637,224.96/12 = $303,102.08.
